<center>
<table width="600">
	<tr>
		<td>
			<h1 align="center">Data Flow in a Typical Content-Based Image Retrieval System</h1>
			<hr>			
		
			<h3>Data Flow:</h3>
			<p align="center">
			<img border="0" src="images/cbir-dataflow.GIF" width="570" height="448">
			</p>
			<p>
			<b>1. Annotation and Interact</b><br>
			Images in database are first annotated with keywords to improve performance.
			</p>
			
			<p>
			<b>2. Extraction of Content Description </b>
			<ul>
				<li><b>Image Processing</b> - color, local shape, texture is extracted 
				from the image.</li>
				<li><b>Feature Extraction</b> - data&nbsp; from image processing is 
				group together to form features.</li>
			</ul>	
			</p>
			
			<p>
			<b>3. Indexing</b><br>
			- Images are indexed based features extracted from each image.  <br>
			- Note: not all image retrieval build index.  <br>
			- IBM's QBIC is among the first to use index to improve the speed of image retrieval
			</p>
			
			
			<p>
			<b>4. Similarity Comparision</b><br>
			- Extracted feature forms a vector space and used to compute a visual fingerprint (or signature).<br>
			- Signatures are compared to determine similarity.<br>
			- In addition to similarity, matching (find same image) or classification  (suggests keywords based on similar image) can be applied
			</p>
		</td>
	</tr>
</table>
</center>

